  "prompt": "Why all planets are circling the sun in the same direction?",
  "response": "The reason all planets in our solar system orbit the Sun in the same direction (counterclockwise when viewed from above the North Pole) is related to the formation of the solar system:\n\n1. Initial Formation Process\n- About 4.6 billion years ago, the solar system began as a rotating disk of gas and dust called a protoplanetary nebula\n- Gravitational forces and angular momentum caused this disk to rotate in a specific direction\n- As the disk collapsed, it began spinning faster (like an ice skater pulling in their arms)\n\n2. Angular Momentum Conservation\n- The initial rotation of the nebula was conserved during planet formation\n- Planets formed from the material in this spinning disk, inheriting its rotational direction\n- This is why all planets orbit in the same direction and mostly lie in the same plane\n\n3. Exceptions and Variations\n- Most moons also orbit in the same direction as their parent planet\n- Some minor exceptions exist, like Venus (which rotates in the opposite direction)\n- Pluto and some outer solar system objects have slight variations\n\nThis uniform direction is a direct result of the solar system's gravitational and rotational dynamics during its initial formation process.",
